      <hedline>
        <hl1>The New Green Building</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Introduction of Times Magazine issue examining ecology of architecture in age of shrinking forests, urban sprawl and rising anxiety about global warming</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>''Simplify, simplify,'' Thoreau once wrote. But is it possible to be green without retreating to a cabin in the woods? This issue looks at the ecology of architecture in the age of shrinking forests, urban sprawl and rising anxiety about global warming: A city in Brazil that made recycling a civic religion. An architect in Australia who looked to the land and its early settlers. An entrepreneur with a plan for every house to generate its own power. A Japanese architect who saw the possibilities in paper. An imaginary future home both luxurious and green. And a new generation of European architects who may show us what to do next.</p>
      </block>
